column62: Defective Component or Device
column168: During loading there was no signs of product leaking.  Driver moved to the customer scale on site and noticed the turpentine smell and then saw a leak coming from the bottom forward section of the insulation through a weep hole.  Driver moved it to the customer containment area on site.  We formulated a game plan with the shipper to transfer it in to a new trailer.  We also brought in a response team to 'diaper' the trailer in the interim to help contain it.  The transload was successful and the trailer stopped leaking and was cleaned and put on the train back to Chicago.
column169: The trailer just arrived in Chicago this week.  It has not been inspected yet but we are confident this will be a barrel leak.  I do not anticipate that the leak is due to corrosion.  I suspect this is due to a crack in a specific spot where the barrel recieves the most impact pressure when they are lifted on and off the train.  There is a reinforcement kit that will be installed when / if that is the case.  I will update this form once we have confirmation on the root cause - corrective actions.

column62: Forklift Accident
column168: XPO Logistics terminal NBM experienced a UN3266 Zep Concentrated Driveway and Concrete Cleaner release from a box containing (4) 1-gallon poly jugs. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-gallon of product released impacting the trailer floor and cardboard box due to a fork blade puncture. The crew advised the release evaporated and there was no product to clean off of the floor of the trailer. The damaged jug and impacted cardboard were containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The remaining cargo was re-secured for shipment on. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-pound of product released impacting a 2' x 2' area of the trailer floor due to a pallet puncture. The damaged bags, released product, and impacted pallet pieces were containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The remaining cargo was re-secured for shipment on. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal UDV experienced a UN2924 "M2488" release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup and a tote transfer.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 12-ounces of product released impacting a 1' x 1' area of the dock floor due to a crack on the top corner of the tote. Crew began by neutralizing the released product with a soda ash solution and using spill pads to collect all free-standing liquid. The product was then transferred into a new tote for shipment on. The damaged tote was cut up and containerized along with the spill pads and PPE into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.
